Do the methods have to be static?

If not, and the methods are related you could create a wrapper class to reduce duplicating code. This would simply look like:

```java
public class GenericWrapper&lt;T extends A &amp; B&gt; {
	public void method1(T t1, T t2) {
		// Your code here. The parameters to this method could be anything.
	}
	public void method2(T t) {}
}
```

You then can reference the generic type T in method1 and method2. The Wrapper class may even suite well as a nested class.

To call the methods it would look something like:

```java
GenericWrapper&lt;MyClass&gt; wrapper = new GenericWrapper&lt;MyClass&gt;();

wrapper.method1(new MyClass(), new MyClass());
wrapper.method2(new MyClass());
```
The above is using the example parameters to the methods, in reality they may be anything.

Note this solution only works if the functions are not required to be static.

